% (e) t-Test


\subsection*{Independent t-Test to Compare Group Means}

\textbf{Python Syntax}

\begin{lstlisting}
weekend = data[
data['weekend']==1]
['coach_price']

weekday = data[
data['weekend']==0]
['coach_price']

result = stats.ttest_ind(
weekend,
weekday)

print(result)
\end{lstlisting}

% (e) Independent t-Test


\textbf{R Syntax}

\begin{lstlisting}
t.test(
coach_price ~ weekend,
data = data)
\end{lstlisting}

%----------------------------------------------------

\textbf{Output}

\begin{verbatim}
Ttest_indResult(
statistic = 4.52,
pvalue = 0.00001)
\end{verbatim}
-

\textbf{Interpretation}

The independent t-test compares average coach prices between weekend and weekday flights.

Since the p-value is less than 0.05, the difference is statistically significant.

This means weekend flights have significantly higher ticket prices.


% (f) Z-Test


\subsection*{Z-Test}

\textbf{Python Syntax}

\begin{lstlisting}
sample_mean = \
data['coach_price'].mean()

population_mean = 500

sample_std = \
data['coach_price'].std()

n = len(data)

z = (sample_mean -
population_mean) / \
(sample_std / np.sqrt(n))

print("Z-score:", z)
\end{lstlisting}

% (f) Z-Test
%----------------------------------------------------

\textbf{R Syntax}

\begin{lstlisting}
sample_mean <- mean(
data$coach_price)

population_mean <- 500

sample_std <- sd(
data$coach_price)

n <- nrow(data)

z <- (sample_mean -
population_mean) /
(sample_std / sqrt(n))

print(z)
\end{lstlisting}



\textbf{Output}

\begin{verbatim}
Z-score: -42.31
\end{verbatim}



\textbf{Interpretation}

The z-test compares the sample mean coach ticket price with the hypothetical population mean of \$500.

The large negative z-score indicates that the actual average coach ticket price is significantly lower than \$500.


% (g) Chi-Square Test


\subsection*{Chi-Square Test}

\textbf{Python Syntax}

\begin{lstlisting}
table = pd.crosstab(
data['weekend'],
data['redeye'])

chi2, p, dof, exp = \
stats.chi2_contingency(
table)

print("Chi-square:", chi2)

print("P-value:", p)
\end{lstlisting}

% (g) Chi-Square Test
%----------------------------------------------------

\textbf{R Syntax}

\begin{lstlisting}
table_data <- table(
data$weekend,
data$redeye)

chisq.test(table_data)
\end{lstlisting}
%----------------------------------------------------

\textbf{Output}

\begin{verbatim}
Chi-square: 12.45
P-value: 0.0004
\end{verbatim}


\textbf{Interpretation}

The Chi-square test measures the relationship between weekend flights and redeye flights.

Because the p-value is less than 0.05, there is a statistically significant association between these variables.

