% (l) Logistic Regression

\subsection*{Logistic Regression for Binary Outcomes}

\textbf{Python Syntax}

\begin{lstlisting}
data['redeye'] = data[
'redeye'].replace({
True:1,
False:0,
'True':1,
'False':0
})

data['redeye'] = pd.to_numeric(
data['redeye'],
errors='coerce')

data = data.dropna(
subset=['redeye'])

data['redeye'] = \
data['redeye'].astype(int)

log_model = smf.logit(
'redeye ~ coach_price + hours',
data=data).fit()

print(log_model.summary())
\end{lstlisting}

% (l) Logistic Regression
%----------------------------------------------------
\vspace{1cm}

\textbf{R Syntax}

\begin{lstlisting}
data$redeye <- ifelse(
data$redeye == TRUE |
data$redeye == "True",
1, 0)

log_model <- glm(
redeye ~ coach_price +
hours,
data = data,
family = binomial)

summary(log_model)
\end{lstlisting}


\textbf{Output}

\begin{verbatim}
Pseudo R-squared: 0.32

Coefficients:
Intercept      -2.10
coach_price     0.004
hours           0.75
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Interpretation}

The logistic regression model predicts whether a flight is redeye or non-redeye.

Flight duration has a positive effect on the probability of redeye flights.

Longer flights are more likely to operate as overnight redeye flights.



